\section{Stopping-power ratio prediction for mixtures}

\begin{figure}
	\centering
	\includegraphics[width=0.49\textwidth]{Figure1a.pdf}
	\includegraphics[width=0.49\textwidth]{Figure1b.pdf}
	\caption{I-value dependence (left) and energy dependence (right) of the relative stopping number according to \eref{eq:stopping_number} with $I_w = 75$ eV. The I-value range relevant for tissue is shaded in yellow.}
	\label{fig:1}
\end{figure}

We propose to view the stopping-power ratio as the product of the relative electron density, {\ensuremath{\widehat{n}}\xspace}, and the relative stopping number, {\ensuremath{\widehat{L}}\xspace}, according to \eref{eq:SPR}. We show in \citeasnoun{Moehler} how the relative electron density can be directly determined from DECT for basically any compound or mixture in a robust method. Here in contrast, we focus on the indirect determination of relative stopping numbers, where mixing has to be explicitly taken into account.

Due to the limited possible difference of $I$ from $I_w$ in human tissue and the logarithmic dependence of {\ensuremath{\widehat{L}}\xspace} on $I$, {\ensuremath{\widehat{L}}\xspace} is naturally bounded within a small interval around unity. For a generic therapeutic particle-beam energy of $T=200$ MeV/u, {\ensuremath{\widehat{L}}\xspace} is confined between about 0.7 and 1.15 if all elements up to $Z=100$ are considered (\fref{fig:1}). In the restricted I-value range of real tissue, from about 63 eV (adipose) up to 112 eV (cortical bone), the interval shrinks down considerably to about 0.95 to 1.02, as discussed in detail below.

\Fref{fig:1} also visualizes the dependence of the relative stopping number on the beam energy, which is generally weaker than the I-value dependence in the relevant respective ranges, but gets more significant towards lower energies. It is difficult to accurately account for this effect in current treatment planning systems, as the I-value and energy-dependence cannot be easily separated with a static HLUT. This separation, however, is straightforward in DECT-based range prediction. In consequence, relative stopping numbers can be provided adapting to the decreasing energy of particles during their path in tissue. Whether this leads to a significant improvement depends on particle field configurations and the tissue traversed and therefore has to be studied with realistic clinical cases in the future.


