A maximum uncertainty of $0.6\%$ ($1.0\%$) is reached with this particular calibration considering body tissues (tissue base components) as the base materials. Additional sources of uncertainty are the limited validity of Bragg's additivity rule and the uncertainty of the calculated ({\ensuremath{\widehat{\sigma}}\xspace}, {\ensuremath{\widehat{L}}\xspace})-positions of the base points that are used for the calibration itself. Combining $u_{{\ensuremath{\widehat{L}}\xspace}}$ with the uncertainty of the electron-density determination from \citeasnoun{Huenemohr2014a}, $u_{{\ensuremath{\widehat{n}}\xspace}} = 0.4\%$, yields a maximum uncertainty of the stopping-power prediction of $0.7\%$ ($1.1\%$) for arbitrary mixtures of body tissues (tissue base components).


\section{Conclusion and outlook}

Heterogeneities and tissue mixtures occur naturally in voxels of patient CT images and therefore have to be considered properly in any method for DECT-based ion-range prediction suitable for clinical application. We showed how this can be achieved by relating the I-value dependent relative stopping number to the relative cross section obtained from a DECT scan. Our approach makes a robust quantification of uncertainties possible by exploiting the mathematical structure of the considered ({\ensuremath{\widehat{\sigma}}\xspace}, {\ensuremath{\widehat{L}}\xspace}) variable space.

The presented results can be seamlessly complemented by experiments, performing a DECT scan of appropriate samples for electron-density determination and a range measurement at an ion-beam line. Experimental constraints are hereby relaxed to a certain degree by the electron density dropping out of the equations, allowing for more flexibility in the choice and handling of samples.



